Think carefully about how a code quality tool should handle and communicate uncertainty in its findings. Most static analysis tools present their findings as definitive facts ("this function has cyclomatic complexity of 15, which exceeds the threshold of 10") when in reality many findings involve heuristic judgments with varying confidence levels. A god class detector might flag a class as a god class with 70% confidence based on size and coupling heuristics, but a developer who disagrees will lose trust in the entire tool.

Reason through the following dimensions of uncertainty in static analysis. First, measurement uncertainty: for metrics with objective definitions like cyclomatic complexity, there is no uncertainty in the measurement itself (given a correct parser), but there is uncertainty in whether the metric threshold represents a meaningful quality boundary. How should a tool communicate that the threshold is a policy choice, not a law of nature? Second, detection uncertainty for pattern-based smells: code smell detection involves matching heuristic patterns against code structure. A Long Method detection at 52 lines when the threshold is 50 is much less certain to be a real quality problem than a detection at 200 lines. Should findings include confidence scores or distance-from-threshold information? Third, the false positive problem in safety-critical contexts: a thread safety warning or a bug detection warning that turns out to be a false positive is worse than no warning at all, because it trains developers to ignore warnings in that category. Should these high-stakes detections be held to a higher confidence threshold than stylistic findings? Fourth, communicating uncertainty to two audiences: the individual developer who sees the finding in their code review and the tech lead who sees the aggregate quality dashboard. These two audiences need different information — the developer needs to know whether to act on a specific finding, while the tech lead needs to know whether the aggregate trend is meaningful signal or noise. Design a concrete uncertainty communication model for both audiences, including what information should accompany each finding and what confidence intervals should appear in the dashboard.
